<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12053k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12053k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12053k"> 53(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> au peril da la mer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">46: Ayant fait un p&egrave;lerinage &agrave; Saint-Jacques de Galice, il avait remarqu&eacute; que &laquo;la plupart des fid&egrave;les du Christ qui se rendaient au <mark>Mont Saint- Michel au p&eacute;ril de la mer</mark>, de toutes les parties du monde, surtout pendant l&apos;&eacute;t&eacute;, &eacute;taient arr&ecirc;t&eacute;s par le flux et le reflux de la mer, ne trouvaient ni passages, ni conducteurs, ni lieux destin&eacute;s pour les recevoir charitablement et o&ugrave; ils pussent reposer la t&ecirc;te&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[Having made a pilgrimage to Saint James in Galicia, he had observed that &ldquo;the greatest part of the faithful of Christ who travel to Mont-Saint-Michel in danger of the sea, from all parts of the world, especially during the summer, were stopped by the ebb and flow of the sea; did not find passage, nor guides, nor places that would offer them shelter and where they could rest&rdquo;.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
